      "question": "In the given figure, $O$ is the centre of a circle. $PA$ and $PB$ are two tangents drawn from an external point $P$ to the circle. If $\\angle APB = 70^\\circ$, find the measure of $\\angle OAB$.",
      "answer": "(A)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "In quadrilateral $OAPB$, the sum of angles is $360^\\circ$. Since tangents are perpendicular to the radius at the point of contact, $\\angle OAP = \\angle OBP = 90^\\circ$.",
          "Calculate $\\angle AOB = 180^\\circ - \\angle APB = 180^\\circ - 70^\\circ = 110^\\circ$.",
          "In $\triangle OAB$, $OA = OB$ (radii of the same circle), which implies $\triangle OAB$ is an isosceles triangle.",
          "The base angles are equal, so $\\angle OAB = \\angle OBA = (180^\\circ - \\angle AOB) / 2$.",
          "Calculate $\\angle OAB = (180^\\circ - 110^\\circ) / 2 = 70^\\circ / 2 = 35^\\circ$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$PA \\perp OA \\text{ and } PB \\perp OB \\Rightarrow \\angle OAP = \\angle OBP = 90^\\circ \\\\ \text{In quad } OAPB, \\angle AOB = 360^\\circ - (90^\\circ + 90^\\circ + 70^\\circ) = 110^\\circ \\\\ OA = OB \\Rightarrow \triangle OAB \\text{ is isosceles} \\\\ \\angle OAB = \\angle OBA \\\\ \\angle OAB + \\angle OBA + \\angle AOB = 180^\\circ \\\\ 2 \\angle OAB = 180^\\circ - 110^\\circ \\\\ \\angle OAB = 35^\\circ$"
      },
